}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 113 "4.  Sol
ving Equations in One Variable.   There are two different commands to \+
direct Maple to solve an equation:  " }{TEXT 285 5 "solve" }{TEXT -1 
5 " and " }{TEXT 286 7 "fsolve." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 35 "They h
ave different purposes.  The " }{TEXT 287 5 "solve" }{TEXT -1 63 " com
mand attempts to find exact solutions.  If the expression  " }{TEXT 
289 1 "f" }{TEXT -1 116 "  is defined in terms of only one variable, t
here are several different ways to direct Maple to solve the equation \+
 " }{TEXT 290 5 "f  = " }{TEXT 291 4 "0.  " }{TEXT -1 54 "The followin
g all cause Maple to solve the equation   " }{TEXT 292 5 "f  = " }
{TEXT 293 2 "0." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 7 "       " }{TEXT 311 9 "solve(f);" }}{PARA 258 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 18 "       solve(f,x);" }}{PARA 258 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 18 "    \+
   solve(f=0);" }}{PARA 258 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 20 "       solve(f=0,x);
" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 349 "Mapl
e makes an assumption that if the coefficients of a polynomial are all
 given exactly (as integers or rational numbers [ratios of integer]), \+
then you are only interested in finding exact solutions.  The Fundamen
tal Theorem of Algebra doesn't guarantee that the solutions of  a poly
nomial can be found exactly, only the polynomial has solutions.  " }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 78 "You can f
orce Maple to report additional (approximate) solutions by using the \+
" }{TEXT 288 6 "fsolve" }{TEXT -1 43 " command.  (What does the \"f\" \+
stand for?)  " }{TEXT 312 39 "Does the f stand for floating decimal? \+
" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 254 "  In addition, to forcing Maple to r
eport approximate solutions, you can specify a field extension (typica
lly real or complex) and require Maple to look for solutions which fit
 in that field extension.  Also, one can specify a range of x values a
nd force" }{TEXT 296 7 " fsolve" }{TEXT -1 75 " to only look for solut
ions in that specified range.  For example, compare:" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "
" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 16 "fsolve(4*x
-x^3);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6%$!+++++?!\"*$\"\"!F'$\"+++++
?F%" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 23 "fsolve(4*x-x^3,x=1..
4);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#$\"+++++?!\"*" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 
"" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 28 "For each of the polyno
mials " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "p[1]" "6#&%\"pG6#\"\"\"" }{TEXT -1 9 " through
 " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "p[14]" "6#&%\"pG6#\"#9" }{TEXT -1 19 ", do the foll
owing:" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 56 "     a.   solve for all exact r
oots whereever possible, " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 59 "     b.   fi
nd all approximate roots to 10 decimal places, " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 43 "     c.  factor each into linear factors.  " }}{PARA 0 "
" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 106 "You will need to \+
click on  [> in the toolbar to obtain new execution lines just below t
he cursor position." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 37 "Notice that these \+
are not P1:=x^2-2  " }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 14 "p[1] \+
:= x^2-2;" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#>&%\"pG6#\"\"\",&*$)%\"xG
