{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 1 " " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 56 "5.  Solv
ing Systems of Equations in Several Variables.  " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 49 "When we have an equation \+
in two variables, e.g.  " }{XPPEDIT 19 1 "3*x -2*y = 5" "6#/,&*&\"\"$
\"\"\"%\"xGF'F'*&\"\"#F'%\"yGF'!\"\"\"\"&" }{TEXT -1 147 "  we often a
ssociate with it a graph, the set of points (x,y) in the two-dimension
al plane which satisfy the equation.  For a linear equation like " }
{XPPEDIT 19 1 "3*x-2*y = 5" "6#/,&*&\"\"$\"\"\"%\"xGF'F'*&\"\"#F'%\"yG
F'!\"\"\"\"&" }{TEXT -1 89 " the graph is a straight line.  For more a
 complicated equation in two variables, e.g.,  " }{XPPEDIT 19 1 "2*x^3
 -3*x + y^2 = x*y" "6#/,(*&\"\"#\"\"\"*$%\"xG\"\"$F'F'*&F*F'F)F'!\"\"*
$%\"yGF&F'*&F)F'F.F'" }{TEXT -1 45 "  the graph becomes a more complic
ated curve." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 
-1 282 "When we have two equations in two variables, we think of the s
olution set of this system of equations as being the set of points (x,
y) which satisfy both equations simultaneously.  In terms of their gra
phs, the solution set is the set of points where the graphs intersect \+
(cross).  " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 
-1 622 "When we have two linear equations in two variables, since thei
r graphs are straight lines, then two straight lines, if they cross, w
ill cross in exactly one place.  Hence, the solution set of the system
 of equations will be exactly one point (x,y).  If we have two equatio
ns which are more complicated, then the number of intersection points \+
(crossing points) of their graphs can vary.  For example, if the graph
 of one equation is a circle and the graph of the other equation is a \+
straight line, then, if their graphs cross, then number of solutions (
intersection points) of the system of equations could be 1 or 2.  Etc.
" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 128 "We c
an instruct Maple to find solutions of systems of equations using the \+
solve or fsolve commands.  The syntax for doing so is:" }}{PARA 0 "" 
0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 30 "     solve( \{eq1,eq
2\}, \{x,y\});" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 1 " " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 85 "where eq1 and eq2 are equations in the variables x and y.
  This is illustrated below." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}
{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 42 "solve(\{ x + 2*y = 5, 2*x-3*
y = -1\},\{x,y\});" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#<$/%\"yG#\"#6\"
\"(/%\"xG#\"#8F(" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 22 "We could have defined " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }
}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 
0 40 "eq1 := x + 2*y = 5;\neq2 := 2*x-3*y = -1;" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" 
{XPPMATH 20 "6#>%$eq1G/,&%\"xG\"\"\"*&\"\"#F(%\"yGF(F(\"\"&" }}{PARA 
11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#>%$eq2G/,&*&\"\"#\"\"\"%\"xGF)F)*&\"\"$F)%\"
yGF)!\"\"F." }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 
-1 26 "and then given the command" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 
25 "solve( \{eq1,eq2\}, \{x,y\});" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#<
$/%\"yG#\"#6\"\"(/%\"xG#\"#8F(" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 55 "and achieved the same result.  Remember t
he solution  (" }{XPPEDIT 19 1 "13/7" "6#*&\"#8\"\"\"\"\"(!\"\"" }
{TEXT -1 2 ", " }{XPPEDIT 19 1 "11/7" "6#*&\"#6\"\"\"\"\"(!\"\"" }
{TEXT -1 127 ") represents a point in the two-dimensional plane (why t
wo-dimensional?) where the graphs of the equations intersect (cross). \+
 " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 63 "Find
 the solutions, if they exist, for the following equations " }}{PARA 
0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 4 "a.  " }{XPPEDIT 
19 1 "3*x - 2*y = 6" "6#/,&*&\"\"$\"\"\"%\"xGF'F'*&\"\"#F'%\"yGF'!\"\"
\"\"'" }{TEXT -1 3 ",  " }{XPPEDIT 19 1 "4*x + y = -2" "6#/,&*&\"\"%\"
\"\"%\"xGF'F'%\"yGF',$\"\"#!\"\"" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 
1 0 37 "eq1:= 3*x-2*y = 6;  eq2:= 4*x+y = -2;" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" 
{XPPMATH 20 "6#>%$eq1G/,&*&\"\"$\"\"\"%\"xGF)F)*&\"\"#F)%\"yGF)!\"\"\"
